## Key Architectural Patterns

### 1. **Tool Registration Pattern**
```csharp
// C# side (PlaytestServer.cs)
new SimulateInputTool()  // Instantiate once in Awake
_tools.Add(name, tool)   // Register by name

// TypeScript side (index.ts)
registerSimulateInputTool(server, playtestUnity, logger)
server.tool(name, description, schema, async handler)
```

### 2. **Sync vs Async Execution**
```csharp
// Sync tools (PlayModeControlTool, QueryGameStateTool)
IsAsync = false
Execute(params) â†’ return JObject

// Async tools (SimulateInputTool)
IsAsync = true
ExecuteAsync(params, tcs) â†’ tcs.SetResult(JObject) when done
```

### 3. **WebSocket Persistence Through Play Mode**
```csharp
[InitializeOnLoad] â†’ runs at editor startup
[DidReloadScripts] â†’ after domain reload, check if was running
SessionState.SetBool() â†’ persists key/value pairs across reloads
PlayModeStateChanged event â†’ save state before reload, restore after
```

### 4. **Input Injection Strategies** (InputSimulator.cs)
```csharp
// Priority 1: InputSystem gamepad device
InputState.Change(gamepad.leftStick, value) â†’ most reliable

// Priority 2: Direct reflection on PlayerController
field.SetValue(controller, value) â†’ fallback for testing

// Both methods work; gamepad is preferred for input system integration
```

### 5. **Runtime State Access from Editor**
```csharp
// During Play Mode, editor code can access runtime singletons
GameManager.instance â†’ works in editor code during Play Mode
FindObjectsByType<PlayerController>() â†’ works in editor code
```

