## How simulate_input Works (Full Flow)

### Client Call (TypeScript)
```typescript
// tools/simulateInputTool.ts:42-46
const response = await playtestUnity.sendRequest({
  method: "simulate_input",
  params: { action: "move", playerIndex: 0, value: {x: 0.5, y: 0.5}, duration: 0.1 }
});
```

### WebSocket Transport (PlaytestUnity.ts)
```typescript
// src/unity/playtestUnity.ts:180-216
sendRequest() {
  - Generates UUID for correlation
  - Connects if needed (auto-reconnect)
  - Sends JSON: {id: uuid, method: "simulate_input", params: {...}}
  - Waits for response with matching id or 30s timeout
}
```

### Unity Socket Handler
```csharp
// PlaytestSocketHandler.cs:36-79
OnMessage() {
  - Parses JSON
  - Extracts method ("simulate_input") and params
  - Calls _server.TryGetTool("simulate_input", out tool)
  - Dispatches: EditorCoroutineUtility.StartCoroutineOwnerless(ExecuteTool())
}

ExecuteTool() {
  - For async tools: tool.ExecuteAsync(params, tcs)
  - tcs.Task completes when tool finishes
  - Sends response back via WebSocket
}
```

### Tool Execution
```csharp
// SimulateInputTool.cs:18-48
ExecuteAsync() {
  - Validates action and playerIndex
  - Checks EditorApplication.isPlaying
  - Schedules: EditorApplication.delayCall += () => {
      InputSimulator.SimulateAction(action, playerIndex, value, duration)
    }
}

// InputSimulator.cs:23-48
SimulateAction() {
  switch (action) {
    case "move":
      - FindPlayerController(playerIndex)
      - Get PlayerInput component and devices
      - If gamepad found: InputState.Change(gamepad.leftStick, value)
      - If no gamepad: Use reflection to set moveInput property directly
      - Schedule reset after duration
    case "melee_attack" | "ranged_attack" | etc:
      - Map to gamepad button (buttonEast, buttonSouth, etc)
      - InputState.Change(button, 1f) then 0f
      - Or reflection to set backing field
  }
  return {success: true, action, playerIndex, appliedValue, method}
}
```

